fr:mainmatter.fr:p:
We must define the action of \operatorname *{lim}_J on natural
  transformations. A natural transformation F\xrightarrow {\alpha } G defines
  a cone \operatorname *{lim}_J F\to  F\xrightarrow {\alpha } G over G, where
  the first map is the canonical limiting cone over F. By the
  universal property of \operatorname *{lim}_J G, this cone factors uniquely as





    \usepackage{tikz, tikz-cd, mathtools, amssymb}
  \usetikzlibrary{shapes.geometric}
  \usetikzlibrary{calc}
  \usetikzlibrary{matrix}
  \usetikzlibrary{decorations.markings}

  \tikzset{
    % basics
    square/.style={draw, regular polygon, regular polygon sides=4},
    triangle/.style={draw, regular polygon, regular polygon sides=3},
  }

  \tikzset{
    % string diagrams
    state/.style={triangle, shape border rotate=180, anchor=north},
    costate/.style={triangle, anchor=south},
    morphism/.style={draw, rectangle},
    over/.style={
      draw=white,
      double=black,
      % default is .4pt
      line width=1.2pt,
      double distance=.4pt,
      text=black
    },
  }

  \tikzset{ 
    % tables
    % https://tikz.net/tikz-table/
    table/.style={
        matrix of nodes,
        row sep=-\pgflinewidth,
        column sep=-\pgflinewidth,
        nodes={
            rectangle,
            draw=black,
            align=center
        },
        minimum height=1.5em,
        text depth=0.5ex,
        text height=2ex,
        nodes in empty cells,
%%
        every even row/.style={
            nodes={fill=gray!20}
        },
        column 1/.style={
            nodes={font=\bfseries}
        },
        row 1/.style={
            nodes={
                fill=black,
                text=white,
                font=\bfseries
            }
        }
    }
  }


    \begin {tikzcd}
    \operatorname *{lim}_J F\ar [dr, "\operatorname *{lim}_J \alpha "']\ar [r] & F\ar [r, "\alpha "] & G \\
    & \operatorname *{lim}_J G\ar [ur]
    \end {tikzcd}


 The first map defines the action of \operatorname *{lim}_J on
  \alpha .

To see that this defines a functor, given two natural transformations
  F\xrightarrow {\alpha }G\xrightarrow {\beta } H, observe that the map \operatorname *{lim}_J   F\xrightarrow {\operatorname *{lim}_J\alpha }\operatorname *{lim}_J G\xrightarrow {\operatorname *{lim}_J\beta }\operatorname *{lim}_J H 
  factors the cone \operatorname *{lim}_J F\to  F\to  G\to  H:





